# Car Telemetry System — Flink Implementation

## Overview
Evolution of the Kafka multi-topic implementation, replacing scheduled batch
analytics with Apache Flink real-time stream processing.

## Architecture
[Car Producer] → Kafka (car-positions) → Flink Job → MongoDB

## Tech Stack
- **Java 21** + **Apache Flink 2.0.1**
- **Kafka** — message transport (KRaft mode, no Zookeeper)
- **Protobuf** — message serialization
- **MongoDB** — storage for raw data and Flink results
- **Docker** — fully containerized deployment

## Key Differences from kafka-multi-topic Branch
| | kafka-multi-topic | flink |
|---|---|---|
| Analytics | Batch every 10 minutes | Real-time per event |
| State storage | MongoDB | Flink ValueState (memory) |
| Trip detection | Scheduled polling | Event-driven timers |
| Latency | Up to 10 minutes | Milliseconds |
| MongoDB reads | Constant polling | Write only |

## Flink Job — `CarPositionProcessFunction`
**Stateful per-VIN processing:**
- Maintains trip state in Flink `ValueState`
- Detects new trips when state is empty
- Computes haversine distance between consecutive positions
- Detects speed alerts (> 120 kph)
- Uses processing time timers for trip timeout (5 minutes)

## Flink Job - `CarDiagnosticsProcessFunction`
**Stateful per-incident processing:**
- Detects error messages sent by a vehicle
- Each error message can contain multiple "problems" — generates one MongoDB document per problem
- OBD2 error codes are classified by severity:
  - `CRITICAL` — chassis/brakes (C0xxx)
  - `HIGH` — body/powertrain (B0xxx, P0xxx)
  - `MEDIUM` — manufacturer/network (P1xxx, P2xxx, U0xxx)
- Each alert document is placed into `flink_diagnostics_alerts` collection
- Counts warnings received per vehicle — if threshold reached (5 alerts)
  pushes a notification to `flink_critical_warnings` collection

**MongoDB output collections:**
- `flink_completed_trips` — completed trip summaries
- `flink_speed_alerts` — speed violations

## Running the System
```bash
# build all JARs
cd car-consumer && mvn clean package -DskipTests
cd ../car-producer && mvn clean package -DskipTests
cd ../car-flink && mvn clean package -DskipTests
cd ..

# start infrastructure
docker-compose up --build mongodb kafka car-producer jobmanager taskmanager

# submit Flink job
docker cp car-flink/target/car-flink-0.0.1-SNAPSHOT.jar jobmanager:/opt/flink/
docker exec jobmanager flink run /opt/flink/car-flink-0.0.1-SNAPSHOT.jar
```

## Flink UI
http://localhost:8082

## MongoDB Collections
| Collection | Description |
|---|---|
| `car_positions` | Raw GPS positions (written by car-consumer) |
| `car_diagnostics` | Raw diagnostics (written by car-consumer) |
| `flink_completed_trips` | Completed trips (written by Flink) |
| `flink_speed_alerts` | Speed alerts (written by Flink) |

## Environment Variables
| Variable | Default | Description |
|---|---|---|
| `KAFKA_BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS` | `localhost:29092` | Kafka address |
| `MONGODB_URI` | `mongodb://localhost:27017` | MongoDB address |
| `GENERATOR_VEHICLE_COUNT` | `4` | Number of simulated vehicles |

## Why Flink over Scheduled Analytics?
- **No database polling** — state lives in Flink memory
- **True real-time** — trips detected as events arrive
- **Scalable** — add TaskManagers for more throughput
- **Fault tolerant** — Flink checkpointing for state recovery
- **Event-driven timers** — trip timeout handled by Flink, not cron

## Next Steps
